    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-06-18T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-06-18T11:00:00-05:00" n="297"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d297">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.516 Export-Import Bank/6–1847: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Flack</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Paz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-06-18T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 18, 1947—noon.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>580. During past week pressure from Sucre politicians for change in petroleum
                    program was intensified. Consequently I reiterated to Foreign Minister<note
                        n="42" xml:id="d297fn1">Luis Fernando Guachalla.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_Eximbank1">Exim Bank</gloss>’s views as furnished in Dept’s
                    313 of May 29. (Refer <gloss target="#t_mytel1">mytel</gloss> 553 of June
                        10).<note n="43" xml:id="d297fn2">Not printed.</note> In this connection I
                    also had friendly discussion yesterday morning with President Hertzog, who
                    promised that matter would be immediately resolved. Mariaca informed me this
                    morning that at subsequent meeting with Fomento,<note n="44" xml:id="d297fn3"
                        >Corporación Boliviana de Fomento.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_YPFB1">YPFB</gloss> officials and Minister of Economy,
                    President stated that original programs approved would be adhered to and ordered
                    that documents in this connection be prepared promptest possible. This appears
                    to settle whole question.</p>
                <p>However, to satisfy Sucre’s aspirations, Bolivian Government may later seek
                    separately to add to its facilities.</p>
                <p>Dept’s 313 has been most useful since it enabled me to continue discussions
                    without requesting additional instructions.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Lima for Sundt.<note n="45" xml:id="d297fn4">Olaf F. Sundt, Petroleum
                        Attaché assigned to Santiago, Lima, and La Paz.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Flack</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
